<!-- #BeginEditable "Body" -->=20


<h1 class=3D"center">Cross Product</h1>=20


<p>A <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/vectors.html">vector</a>=
 has <b>magnitude</b> (how long it is) and <b>direction</b>:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/v=
ector-mag-dir.svg" alt=3D"vector magnitude and direction" height=3D"137" wi=
dth=3D"267"></p>=20
<p><b>Two vectors</b> <span class=3D"center"> can be <b>multiplied</b> usin=
g the "<b>Cross Product</b>" <i>(also see <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun=
.com/algebra/vectors-dot-product.html">Dot Product</a>)</i></span></p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/v=
ectors-ab.svg" alt=3D"vectors a and b" height=3D"91" width=3D"106"></p>
=20
<p>The Cross Product <b>a =C3=97 b</b> of two vectors is <b>another vector<=
/b> that is at right angles to both:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/c=
ross-product-simple.svg" alt=3D"cross product " height=3D"160" width=3D"145=
"><br>
And it all happens in 3 dimensions!</p>=20
<p>The magnitude (length) of the cross product equals the <a href=3D"https:=
//www.mathsisfun.com/area.html">area of a parallelogram</a> with vectors <b=
>a</b> and <b>b</b> for sides:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/c=
ross-product-area.svg" alt=3D"cross product area" height=3D"234" width=3D"2=
16"></p>=20
<p>See how it changes for different angles:</p>=20

=20

<div style=3D"position:relative; width:240px; min-height:240px; border: non=
e; border-radius: 20px; background-color: #eeeeff; margin:auto; display:blo=
ck;"><canvas id=3D"canvasId" style=3D"position: absolute; width:240px; heig=
ht:240px; left: 0; top:; border: none;" width=3D"480" height=3D"480"></canv=
as><div style=3D"position:absolute; right:15px; top:8px;"><button id=3D"pla=
yBtn" class=3D"btn pause"></button></div><div id=3D"copyrt" style=3D"positi=
on: absolute; right:0px; top:40px; font: 10px Arial; color: #6600cc; transf=
orm: rotate(-90deg); transform-origin: right bottom 0;">=C2=A9 2018 MathsIs=
Fun.com  v0,77</div></div>=20

<p>The cross product (<i style=3D"color:blue">blue</i>) is:</p>=20
<ul class=3D"large">=20
	<li>zero in length when vectors <b>a</b> and <b>b</b> point in the same, o=
r opposite, direction</li>=20
	<li>reaches maximum length when vectors <b>a</b> and <b>b</b> are at right=
 angles</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>And it can point one way or the other!</p>=20
<p>So how do we calculate it?</p>=20


<h2>Calculating</h2>=20

<h4>We can calculate the Cross Product this way:</h4>=20

<p class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/=
cross-product.svg" alt=3D"cross product with angle and unit vector" height=
=3D"160" width=3D"145"></p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger"><b>a =C3=97 b</b> <em>=3D</em> |<b>a</b>| |<b>b<=
/b>| sin(=CE=B8) <b>n</b></p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>|<b>a</b>| is the magnitude (length) of vector <b>a</b></li>=20
	<li>|<b>b</b>| is the magnitude (length) of vector <b>b</b></li>=20
	<li>=CE=B8 is the angle between <b>a</b> and <b>b</b></li>=20
	<li><b>n</b> is the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/vector-u=
nit.html">unit vector</a> at right angles to both <b>a</b> and <b>b</b></li=
>=20
</ul>=20
<p>So the <b>length</b> is: the length of <b>a</b> times the length of <b>b=
</b> times the sine of the angle between <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>,</p>=20
<p>Then we multiply by the vector <b>n</b> so it heads in the correct <b>di=
rection</b> (at right angles to both <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>).</p>=20
<div class=3D"gap"></div>

<h4>OR we can calculate it this way:</h4>=20

<p class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/=
cross-product-components.svg" alt=3D"cross product components" height=3D"24=
3" width=3D"289"></p>=20
<p>When <b>a</b> and <b>b</b> start at the origin point (0,0,0), the Cross =
Product will end at:</p>=20
<ul class=3D"disc">=20
	<li><b>c<sub>x</sub> <em>=3D</em> a<sub>y</sub>b<sub>z</sub> =E2=88=92 a<s=
ub>z</sub>b<sub>y</sub></b></li>=20
	<li><b>c<sub>y</sub> <em>=3D</em> a<sub>z</sub>b<sub>x</sub> =E2=88=92 a<s=
ub>x</sub>b<sub>z</sub></b></li>=20
	<li><b>c<sub>z</sub> <em>=3D</em> a<sub>x</sub>b<sub>y</sub> =E2=88=92 a<s=
ub>y</sub>b<sub>x</sub></b></li>=20
</ul>
<div style=3D"clear:both"></div>

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: The cross product of <b>a</b> <em>=3D</em> (2,3,4) and <b>b</=
b> <em>=3D</em> (5,6,7)</h3>=20

	<ul class=3D"disc">=20
		<li>c<sub>x</sub> <em>=3D</em> a<sub>y</sub>b<sub>z</sub> =E2=88=92 a<sub=
>z</sub>b<sub>y</sub> <em>=3D</em> 3=C3=977 =E2=88=92 4=C3=976 <em>=3D</em>=
 =E2=88=923</li>=20
		<li>c<sub>y</sub> <em>=3D</em> a<sub>z</sub>b<sub>x</sub> =E2=88=92 a<sub=
>x</sub>b<sub>z</sub> <em>=3D</em> 4=C3=975 =E2=88=92 2=C3=977 <em>=3D</em>=
 6</li>=20
		<li>c<sub>z</sub> <em>=3D</em> a<sub>x</sub>b<sub>y</sub> =E2=88=92 a<sub=
>y</sub>b<sub>x</sub> <em>=3D</em> 2=C3=976 =E2=88=92 3=C3=975 <em>=3D</em>=
 =E2=88=923</li>=20
	</ul>=20
	<p>Answer: <span class=3D"center"><b>a =C3=97 b</b> =3D</span> (=E2=88=923=
,6,=E2=88=923)</p>=20
	</div>
<div class=3D"gap"></div>
<p class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/=
right-hand-rule.jpg" alt=3D"right hand rule" height=3D"188" width=3D"164"><=
/p>=20


<h2>Which Direction?</h2>=20

<p>The cross product could point in the completely opposite direction and s=
till be at right angles to the two other vectors, so we have the:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><span class=3D"large">"Right Hand Rule"</span></p>=20
<p>With your right-hand, point your index finger along vector <b>a</b>, and=
 point your middle finger along vector <b>b</b>: the cross product goes in =
the direction of your thumb.</p>=20
<div class=3D"gap"></div>


<h2>Dot Product</h2>=20

<p>The Cross Product gives a <b>vector</b> answer, and is sometimes called =
the <b>vector product</b>.</p>=20
<p>But there is also the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/vect=
ors-dot-product.html">Dot Product</a> which gives a <b>scalar</b> (ordinary=
 number) answer, and is sometimes called the <b>scalar product</b>.</p>=20
<div class=3D"gap"></div>
<div class=3D"fun">=20
<div class=3D"floatLt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/images/style/=
smile.svg" alt=3D"joke" height=3D"48" width=3D"48"></div>
<p>Question: What do you get when you cross an elephant with a banana?</p>=
=20
<p><span class=3D"center">Answer: |<b>elephant</b>| |<b>banana</b>| sin(=CE=
=B8) <b>n</b></span></p>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"gap"></div>

